(Description)
Given the heads of two singly linked-lists headA and headB, return the node at which the two lists intersect. 
If the two linked lists have no intersection at all, return null.

For example, the following two linked lists begin to intersect at node c1

--- Solution ---
public class Solution {
    public ListNode getIntersectionNode(ListNode headA, ListNode headB) {
        if (headA == null || headB == null) return null;

        ListNode pA = headA;
        ListNode pB = headB;

        while (pA != pB) {
            pA = (pA == null) ? headB : pA.next;
            pB = (pB == null) ? headA : pB.next;
        }

        return pA;
    }
}

--- Approach ---
Teneray Operator was key role in this solution to link the end and the begin of Linked lists.
In this case, if the intersection exist in anywhere, the linked lists will form the cycle,
while the link will be finished at one time.

Using the concept, if two linked lists form the cycle, pA and PB will meet any point, 
then when they meet at first is right the beginning point of their intersections.
